<h2>
    <a href="/blog/the-babylonian-spiral/">The Babylonian spiral</a>
</h2>




<h6 class="post-meta">
    Posted by:
    
    <a href="/blog/author/christian/">christian</a>
    
    
    
    in
    
    <a href="/blog/category/featured-on-frontpage/">Featured on frontpage</a>
    
    
    
    on 22 May 2020
</h6>





<a href="/blog/the-babylonian-spiral/">
    <img class="img-thumbnail pull-left" src="/static/media/uploads/blog/babylonian-spiral/.thumbnails/babylonian-spiral-2000.png/babylonian-spiral-2000-90x90.png">
</a>





<p>A Babyonian spiral (<a href="https://oeis.org/A256111">OEIS A256111</a>) is the figure formed by starting with a zero-vector at the origin and concatenating vectors such that each subsequent vector is the next one longer than the previous one that also lands on a position with integral Cartesian coordinates. That is, the $i$th vector has integer components $x_i$ and $y_i$ satisfying, $x_i^2 + y_i^2 = n_i^2 &gt; n_{i-1}^2$. Each vector is chosen such that it minimizes the angular separation from the previous one.</p>




<div class="blog-list-detail">
    
    
    <p>
    <a href="/blog/the-babylonian-spiral/">read more</a>
    
    /
    
    <a href="/blog/the-babylonian-spiral/#comments">
        0 comments
    </a>
    
    
    </p>
</div>




